title: all-out_attack
body:
From the [[Persona]] series starting with [[Persona 3]], a battle mechanic where when all enemies are in "Downed" status, the player is given an option for an "All-Out-Attack", triggering a graphic-cut in and a dust-clouded beat-up animation for high damage.

The sequence is often parodied by both Persona series and non-series alike. It is characterized by split facial profiles, along with often two red exclamation points, "!!".

[[Persona 4]] parody iterations are subtly different from [[Persona 3]] iterations. In Persona 4 parodies the characters sport glasses, whereas Persona 3 does not. Backgrounds are typically checker-patterned, and vary in color.

[[Persona 5]] parodies are a significant departure from the 3 and 4 variants. Rather than the split-screen, character portraits are instead rendered on the debris from a shattered-screen effect. More commonly parodied from Persona 5 is the finishing screens that show up when the All-Out Attack finishes the fight, featuring the character that initiated the attack striking a pose while a personalized message appears on screen in a style specific to that character. [[Persona 3 Reload]] adds a similar finishing screen, albeit with a more restrained aesthetic compared to their P5 predecessors. 

Please only use this tag for multiple characters in a picture, not for single expressions of [[!]].

title: greenling_(fish)
body: The lingcod or ling cod, also known as the buffalo cod or cultus cod, is a fish of the greenling family Hexagrammidae. It is the only extant member of the genus Ophiodon. title: united_states_marine_corps
body:
The [[United States]] Marine Corps (USMC) are one of the five branches of the U.S. Military and subordinate to the [[United states navy|U.S. Navy]]. 

Established in 1775 as the Continental Marines, they would gain the bulk of their fame during [[World War II]] in the Pacific Theater, carrying out a lengthy island-hopping campaign that saw brutal engagements against their Japanese counterparts. 

Their typical purpose in the modern era is to carry out expeditionary and amphibious operations, while many will also guard U.S. embassies around the world. 

The U.S. Marines are known for their aggression in combat and their distinctive internal culture.

title: pedigree
body:
The signature move of former professional wrestler [[Triple H]], a double underhook facebuster.

His on-screen protégé, [[Seth Rollins]] also used this move from 2015-2018 as a finishing move. It became one of his signature moves from 2018 onwards. Ring of Honor and [[All Elite Wrestling]] alumni, and current [[WWE]] wrestler [[CM Punk]] uses a top rope variation which he calls as the [I]Pepsi Plunge[/I].

A lifting version also exists, which has its own variations (such as sitout, kneeling, spinning, or a combination of any of them) as well. These variants are used by [[All Elite Wrestling]] wrestler Christopher Daniels (as the [I]Angel's Wings[/I]), former wrestler Awesome Kong  (as the [I]Implant Buster[/I]), and [[WWE]] wrestler Tommaso Ciampa (as the [I]Fairy Tale Ending[/I]).

title: franklin_d._roosevelt
body:
[b]Franklin Delano Roosevelt[/b], commonly known as [b]FDR[/b], was an American statesman and political leader who served as the 32nd President of the [[united states|United States of America]] from 1933 until his death in 1945. He was a distant cousin to [[Theodore Roosevelt]].

FDR is the longest serving President of United States, who was elected four times and died a few months into his fourth term. He is well known for leading the United States to overcome two global crises, the Great Depression and [[World War II]]. An infection of polio left FDR paralyzed from the waist down, so he is often depicted in a [[wheelchair]], though during his lifetime he made sure to never be seen using one in public.

[i][b]Machine Robo[/b][/i] (マシンロボ) is a long running Japanese transforming [[robot]] toyline first released in 1982 by Popy, a division of Bandai, then later by [[Bandai Namco]] proper. It has spawned several anime series that have been produced in Japan until recent years. 

During the early 80s a large portion of the first line of toys from this franchise were exported to North America as part of Tonka's [[GoBots]] and [i][b]Rock Lords[/b][/i] series, beginning in 1983. The franchise was marketed as [i][b]Robo Machine[/b][/i] in Europe, and [i][b]Machine Men[/b][/i] (or [i][b]Robot Machine Men[/b][/i]) in Australia.

title: fitor
body:
A sentient variable [[robot]] of the [[GoBots]] franchise from the 80s.

[b]Fitor[/b] is an evil member of the GoBot Renegade faction. His alternate mode is a red, silver and black futuristic [[jet]] [[aircraft]].

In Japan, his original [[Machine Robo]] name is [b]Machine Jet Robo[/b] or simply [b]Jet Robo[/b], and he is an heroic [[sword]]-wielding protagonist character in that series.

Fitor was featured prominently in the 1986 anime [[machine robo chronos no dai gyakushuu|Machine Robo - Revenge of Cronos]], where he was named [b]Blue Jet[/b] (despite still being red and black) and given portentous [[samurai]] characterisation.

The character was still popular enough that it was again featured in the 2003 [[Machine Robo Rescue]] anime with a new improved design.

He is known for his lanky appearance (282 cm/9'3", 55 kg/121 lbs), cartoonish behavior and abilities, using a giant scalpel as a weapon and the paper bag he wears on his head.

The central characters are [[Sawamura Seiji]], a tough but lonely delinquent known for beating people up with his "Devil's Right Hand," and [[Kasugano Midori]], a shy girl who (apparently due to her unrequited love for Seiji) wakes up one morning in a miniature-sized version of her real body, attached to Seiji's arm where his right hand was.

Adding to the complications are numerous characters with designs (usually romantic, but not always) on Seiji, the original Midori, or the Midori on Seiji's arm.  Primary among these is [[Ayase Takako]], a strait-laced classmate of Seiji's who initially despises him as a delinquent, but after he rescues her from a gang, develops a deep secret crush on him and starts a series of increasingly outlandish schemes to win his affection.

title: 506th_parachute_infantry_regiment_(us_army)
body:
One of three parachute regiments that made up the [[101st Airborne]] during [[World War II]], the [b]506th[/b] saw combat service from the D-Day invasion to the end of the war in Europe, and continues as part of the 101st Airmobile Division today. The regiment was made famous thanks in part to the television series [[Band of Brothers]], which focused on the regiment's E Company ("Easy") during WW2.

Depictions of the regiment will almost invariably be of its appearance in World War II, with the "Screaming Eagle" patch of the 101st Airborne worn on the left shoulder. The major visual indicator of the 506th is the "spade" insignia (from a deck of cards) on the helmet, which was done before the Normandy landings to allow for easy identification. (The division's other regiments - two parachute and glider - used the other three card suits on theirs.)

title: pokemon_vega
body:
A [[Pokemon|Pokémon]] ROM hack built upon the foundation of [[Pokemon FRLG|Pokémon Fire Red]], originally released in 2010. It is the sequel to [[Pokemon Altair and Sirius|Pokémon Altair & Sirius]]. As of 2016, the hack has had an English-language port, with translation work having been conducted on the Nuzlocke Forums.

Pokémon Vega broke new ground in 2010 by introducing the physical/special split to GBA Pokémon and utilizing a number of then-new Pokémon from [[Pokemon BW|Generation V]]. It expanded upon the many [[Fakemon|custom Pokémon]] introduced in its prequels and added a substantial number of new ones, adding up to a full Pokédex of 386.

The game takes place in a brand-new, custom region named Tohoak, a land completely covered in snow. The story references many events from the [[Pokemon (anime)|Pokémon anime movies]] on top of its own core conflict, in which the player must take down Team Dark Hole and their ambition to use the Meteoric Pokémon for nefarious ends.

title: zao_(cruiser)
body:
A fictional name for Japan's Tier 10 heavy cruiser in [i][[World of Warships]][/i]. Named for Mount Zaou (蔵王山), in keeping with the IJN naming convention that heavy cruisers were named after mountains in Japan. Zao is known for having guns with very good muzzle velocity, nicknamed "railguns" by players. 

h4. History
It is actually debatable as to whether or not plans for [i]Zaou[/i] actually existed due to the destruction of sensitive information by the IJN prior to surrender. What is known is that a triple 203 mm gun mount, never actually mounted on any Japanese CA, was considered for eight ships planned under the Sixth Naval Armaments Program but no other information has survived. Certain postwar sources such as [i]Japanese Cruisers of the Pacific War[/i] and [i]Uncompleted Fleet Plan - 1917~1950[/i], from where the [i]Zaou[/i] design was based from, are informed guesses. These sources also give the class name as the [i]Unzen[/i]-class, of which [i]Zaou[/i] was supposed to be the [b]third[/b] member. 

h4. See also
* [[Unzen (Azur Lane)|]]

title: shirasaya
body:
A [[katana]] blade fitted with a plain wooden grip and sheath ([i]saya[/i]) that, when fitted together, completely conceal the blade and resemble a [[bokken]]. This configuration was intended to be used for storage or transportation of blades, not combat, since in addition to the decorative furniture characteristic of katana, a blade in [i]shirasaya[/i] also lacks a hand guard ([i]tsuba[/i]), making it unsafe to wield. Despite this fact, it's not uncommon for [i]shirasaya[/i] blades to be depicted as weapons in active use.

The signature sword carried by Zatoichi, the blind swordsman and eponymous protagonist of the [[Zatoichi]] films, resembles a  [i]shirasaya[/i]; however, the blade is straight and the purpose of the plain wooden furniture is not to protect it in storage, but rather to disguise it as a blind man's cane.

title: hosokawa_gracia
body:
[b]Akechi Tama[/b], usually referred to as Hosokawa Garasha (細川ガラシャ), (1563 – 25 August 1600) was a member of the aristocratic Akechi family from the Sengoku period. Gracia is best known for her role in the [[Battle of Sekigahara]]; she was considered to be a political hostage to the Western army led by [[Ishida Mitsunari]]. She reneged on committing suicide ([[seppuku]]) because of her Catholic faith, breaking the code of conduct imposed on women of the samurai class.

She was the daughter of [[Akechi Mitsuhide]] and [[Tsumaki Hiroko]], the wife of [[Hosokawa Tadaoki]], and a convert to Catholicism. As the last notable survivor of the Akechi clan, the clan that planned and executed the assassination of [[Oda Nobunaga]], the first "Great Unifier" of Japan, Gracia's death impacted both armies. The incident did much damage to Ishida's reputation, which greatly reduced his chances of recruiting more allies, some of whom were also secretly Christians. Gracia's actions consequently led to Mitsunari's defeat; triggering the events that would lead to the formation of the [[Tokugawa Shogunate]].

title: king_(tekken)

[b]King[/b] is a famous [[luchador]] from [[Mexico]] that appears in the [[Tekken]] 3D fighting game series. 

There are actually two Kings in the series, both of whom wore a [[animal head|jaguar mask]] in matches.

The character was inspired by both legendary Japanese pro wrestler [[Tiger Mask (character)|]], as well as Mexican wrestler [i]Fray Tormenta[/i], a Catholic [[priest]] who became a masked wrestler in order to support an orphanage. 

King does not speak, per se. Instead, he makes growls and snarls in the manner of a [[jaguar]], which are translated into English subtitles at the bottom of the screen. Interestingly, other characters do not have a problem understanding King, and converse with him as though he was speaking naturally.

An American single-shot, muzzle-loading [[40mm grenade|40mm]] [[underbarrel grenade launcher]]. It was designed to replace the [[M79]], which was a stand-alone weapon. title: karl_urban
body:
Karl-Heinz Urban (born 7 June 1972) is a [[New Zealand]] actor. His career began with appearances in New Zealand films and TV series such as [[Xena: Warrior Princess]]. His first Hollywood role was in the 2002 horror film Ghost Ship. Since then, he has starred in many high-profile movies, including as Éomer in the second and third installments of [[The Lord of the Rings]] trilogy, Vaako in the second and third installments of the Riddick film series, [[Leonard McCoy]] in the [[Star Trek]]  [[star trek: kelvin timeline|film reboot series]] and Skurge in [[Marvel|Marvel Studios']] [[Thor: Ragnarok]].

Since 2019, he has starred as [[Billy Butcher]] in Amazon's superhero streaming television series [[The Boys]].

title: seven_lucky_gods
body:
七福神 ([i]Shichi-Fuku-Jin[/i], lit. Seven Lucky Gods) are the seven gods of fortune in Japan. 

They originated from various mythologies of India and China. However, their myths and shapes are far different from their origins. 

They are often depicted on their ship, the 宝船 ([i]Takarabune[/i], lit. Treasure Ship). According to Japanese folklore, if you want to dream a lucky "[i]hatsuyume[/i],":http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hatsuyume you shall put a picture of Takarabune under your pillow. 

[[Bishamonten]], [[Benzaiten (mythology)|]] and [[ebisu_(mythology)|Ebisu]] are often worshipped independently.
